[7] Cholera - Myanmar (Shan State)
Date: Wed 25 Nov 2015
Source: Myanmar Times [edited]
http://www.mmtimes.com/index.php/national-news/17810-more-suspected-cholera-outbreaks-reported.html

Local politicians and relief workers in central Shan State have reported 2 suspected outbreaks of cholera among villagers displaced by the fighting that is focused on 2 townships, Kye-thi and Mine Shu/Mong Shu. Shan Youth Group activist Ko Sai Oo said he was trying to organise medical tests with the help of the United Nations to verify whether the disease was cholera.

Pierre Peron, spokesperson in Myanmar for the UN Office for the Coordination of Humanitarian Affairs (OCHA), said the UN had received reports of a number of cases of diarrhea at 1 of the temporary sites hosting displaced civilians. "At this stage, the available information does not indicate that these are cholera cases. However, the Ministry of Health has been informed of the situation and is currently investigating to verify the information," he said.

He said the UN and its humanitarian partners were working with relevant authorities and local organisations to assist with efforts to deliver humanitarian assistance, including health and sanitation. So far UN agencies and international NGOs had already provided 484 hygiene kits, 5000 water purification tablets, 471 family kits, and 493 shelter kits though local partners, the OCHA spokesperson said. "The UN is ready to offer further support once security conditions allow," he added.

[Byline: Guy Dinmore and Thu Thu Aung]

